sVnews
p4
VSri Syamasastri, one of the great Carnatic Music Trinity, was a devotee of Devi Kamakshi. He wrote nearly 300 superb compositions in favour of his favourite deity Bangaru Kamakshi of Thanjavur. He was a master of Tala Sastra and his favorite raga and tala were Anandabhairavi and Misrachapu according to connoisseurs of music.Syamasastri's 184th Vardhanthi was observed devotedly by all senior vidwans of Vijayawada at Sri Sivaramakrishna Kshetram. The programme was organised by Swarajhari Sabha. The programme began with an impressive group singing of selected Syamasastri compositions namely the Begada varnam, the three famous swarajathis of Syamasastri in ragas Bhairavi and more. This was followed by individual renderings of Syamasastri's keertanas by senior musicians like B.V. Durga Bhavani, Popuri Gowrinadh, Vishnubhotla sisters Saraswathi and Krishnaveni. Violin support was provided by P. Nageswara Rao and B.V. Durga Bhavani while M. Lakshminarayana Raju, B.V.S. Prasad and P. Subbaraya Phalgun played mridangams.Maiden programmeA new cultural association emerged in Vijayawada last week. With the joint sponsorship of Abhiruchi, the new Sabha Swara Bharathi made a good beginning by staging a variety music programme at Sri Sivaramakrishna Kshetram. Planned by Sishtla Hymavathi and conducted by S.V.R. Murthy, the programme presented a veena recital by S. Hymavathi and a vocal duet by S. Praveena and S. Bharathi.Hymavathi began her veena concert with Parakela Saraswathi in Natakuranji and followed with Bantureeti (Hamsanadam), Vasudevayani (Kalyani), Neevalla Gunadoshamemi (Kafi) and an Annamacharya keertana.In the vocal duet presented by Praveena and Bharathi, the highlights were Mahaganapathim (Lalita), the well known ragamalika of Swathi Thirunal Bhavayami Raghuramam, Brochevarevarura (Khamas) and the Annamacharya keertana Srimannarayana in Bowli.
